assistantMessages:
I'll place a limit buy (long) order for 0.5 ETH at $3,000 on GMX V2. Let me walk through the steps.

## Step-by-Step Plan

1. Fetch markets and tokens to resolve addresses
2. Find the ETH/USD perpetual market
3. Calculate collateral needed for 0.5 ETH at $3,000
4. Submit a `LimitIncrease` order with trigger price = $3,000

## Code

```typescript
const { GmxSdk } = require("@gmx-io/sdk");
const { createWalletClient, http } = require("viem");
const { privateKeyToAccount } = require("viem/accounts");
const { arbitrum } = require("viem/chains");

async function placeLimitBuyOrder() {
  // ─── Setup ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  const account = privateKeyToAccount(process.env.PRIVATE_KEY);

  const sdk = new GmxSdk({
    chainId: 42161,
    rpcUrl: "https://arb1.arbitrum.io/rpc",
    oracleUrl: "https://arbitrum-api.gmxinfra.io",
    subsquidUrl: "https://gmx.squids.live/gmx-synthetics-arbitrum:prod/api/graphql",
    account: account.address,
    walletClient: createWalletClient({
      account,
      chain: arbitrum,
      transport: http("https://arb1.arbitrum.io/rpc"),
    }),
  });

  // ─── 1. Fetch markets and tokens ──────────────────────────────────────────

  const { marketsInfoData, tokensData } = await sdk.markets.getMarketsInfo();

  // ─── 2. Find ETH/USD perpetual market ─────────────────────────────────────
  // On Arbitrum, the perpetual ETH market uses "WETH" as the index token symbol.
  // Markets with symbol "ETH" are spot-only swap pools — skip those.

  const ethMarket = Object.values(marketsInfoData).find(
    (m) => tokensData[m.indexTokenAddress]?.symbol === "WETH" && !m.isSpotOnly
  );

  if (!ethMarket) throw new Error("ETH/USD perpetual market not found");

  const marketAddress    = ethMarket.marketTokenAddress;
  const longToken        = ethMarket.longTokenAddress;   // WETH — collateral for longs
  const shortToken       = ethMarket.shortTokenAddress;  // USDC

  console.log("Market:      ", marketAddress);
  console.log("Long token:  ", longToken,  `(${tokensData[longToken]?.symbol})`);
  console.log("Short token: ", shortToken, `(${tokensData[shortToken]?.symbol})`);

  // ─── 3. Resolve USDC address ───────────────────────────────────────────────

  const usdcToken = Object.values(tokensData).find((t) => t.symbol === "USDC");
  if (!usdcToken) throw new Error("USDC not found in tokensData");

  // ─── 4. Calculate order parameters ────────────────────────────────────────
  //
  // Target: long 0.5 ETH at $3,000
  //   - Position size  = 0.5 ETH × $3,000 = $1,500
  //   - We use sizeAmount to specify the exact ETH size (18 decimals)
  //   - Collateral paid in USDC; 1x leverage means ~$1,500 USDC collateral
  //   - limitPrice is scaled to 30 decimals: $3,000 → 3000 × 10^30
  //
  // Leverage is set to 10000n (1x) so the full $1,500 is collateral.
  // Adjust leverage (e.g. 20000n = 2x) to reduce required collateral.

  const ETH_SIZE        = 500000000000000000n;           // 0.5 ETH  (18 decimals)
  const LIMIT_PRICE_USD = 3000n * 10n ** 30n;            // $3,000   (30 decimals)
  const LEVERAGE        = 10000n;                        // 1x       (basis points)

  console.log("\nOrder parameters:");
  console.log("  Size:        0.5 ETH");
  console.log("  Limit price: $3,000");
  console.log("  Leverage:    1x");
  console.log("  Collateral:  USDC");

  // ─── 5. Submit limit long order ───────────────────────────────────────────

  const tx = await sdk.orders.long({
    marketAddress,
    payTokenAddress:        usdcToken.address,  // pay with USDC
    collateralTokenAddress: usdcToken.address,  // hold USDC as collateral
    sizeAmount:             ETH_SIZE,           // 0.5 ETH position size
    leverage:               LEVERAGE,
    limitPrice:             LIMIT_PRICE_USD,    // triggers when ETH <= $3,000
    allowedSlippageBps:     50,                 // 0.5% slippage on execution
    skipSimulation:         true,
  });

  console.log("\n✅ Limit order submitted!");
  console.log("   Tx hash:", tx?.hash ?? tx);
  console.log("\nThe order will execute when the ETH oracle price drops to $3,000 or below.");
  console.log("Monitor pending orders with: sdk.orders.getOrders({ marketsInfoData, tokensData })");
}

placeLimitBuyOrder().catch(console.error);
```

## What This Does

| Parameter | Value | Notes |
|-----------|-------|-------|
| Order type | `LimitIncrease` (3) | Created automatically when `limitPrice` is set |
| Direction | Long | ETH price goes up → profit |
| Size | 0.5 ETH | `500000000000000000n` (18 decimals) |
| Trigger price | $3,000 | `3000n * 10n**30n` (30-decimal scaling) |
| Collateral | USDC | Stable collateral for longs is valid on GMX V2 |
| Leverage | 1x | Full collateral backing; increase `leverage` to reduce USDC needed |
| Slippage | 0.5% | Acceptable execution price band around $3,000 |

## Trigger Logic

GMX V2 limit longs trigger when:
```
oracle price <= limitPrice
```
So this order fills when ETH drops to **$3,000 or below** — a classic "buy the dip" entry.

## After Submission

```typescript
// Check if the order is pending
const { ordersInfoData } = await sdk.orders.getOrders({ marketsInfoData, tokensData });
console.log("Pending orders:", Object.values(ordersInfoData).length);

// Cancel if needed
const orderKey = Object.keys(ordersInfoData)[0];
await sdk.orders.cancelOrders([orderKey]);
```

> **Note:** Make sure your wallet holds enough USDC to cover the ~$1,500 collateral plus the execution fee (paid in ETH). The execution fee is typically $0.50–$2.00 on Arbitrum and is refunded if unused.

